Before creating a new file look through the files to make sure one hasn't already been made that could be extended or modified.

1. Project-Wide Connectivity Audit:
   • For each file in the project:
   • Identify all defined functions, methods, and classes.
   • Verify that each is invoked or utilized in other parts of the project.
   • Ensure inter-file dependencies are resolved (e.g., functions or methods defined in one file are accessible and used in relevant files).

2. Functionality and Implementation Validation:
   • Review each file to ensure:
   • Every function has a clear purpose, implementation, and connection to the overall project.
   • Functions perform their intended roles end-to-end, from initialization to final output.
   • Validate that no redundant or unused functions remain unless explicitly marked as deprecated or placeholders for future work.

3. Integration Check:
   • Test the integration of functionality across files:
   • Trace workflows that span multiple files, ensuring proper data flow and processing.
   • Validate that methods like deobfuscate_js() and analyze_code_content() in File A are fully utilized in File B, File C, etc.

4. Documentation and Usability:
   • Ensure every file has:
   • Clear documentation for its purpose and role in the project.
   • Inline comments explaining key functions, especially when they interact with other files.
   • Create or update external documentation to reflect changes across all files.

5. Security and Error Handling:
   • Apply a consistent error-handling and validation approach across all files.
   • Ensure all functions interacting with external inputs are secure against common vulnerabilities (e.g., input sanitization, output validation).
   • Verify that all file operations use secure functions, such as WordPress filesystem functions if applicable.

6. Code Quality and Style Consistency:
   • Confirm adherence to project-wide coding standards:
   • Consistent naming conventions.
   • Proper use of indentation, spacing, and formatting.
   • Ensure the use of standardized libraries or utilities for repeated functionality.

7. Testing and Debugging:
   • Update or create unit tests for all files:
   • Include tests for individual functions.
   • Add end-to-end tests for workflows involving multiple files.
   • Run integration tests to confirm cross-file dependencies function correctly.

8. Refactoring Opportunities:
   • Identify redundant or overlapping functionality across files and consolidate into reusable modules or libraries.
   • Suggest optimizations for repeated code patterns.

9. Final Project Audit:
   • Perform a final pass to confirm:
   • All functions and workflows across files are fully connected.
   • No unused, unconnected, or partially implemented components remain.
   • The project operates as a cohesive whole.
